**Abstract:**
A substantial philosophical essay dated May 1, 1996 titled "Speech Acts Again" critiquing Searle's theory of speech acts and statements. Argues against the view that statements merely "state how things are" as pictures requiring assent. Develops an alternative understanding where statements dispose the addressee to respond practically to things as so-and-so. Uses the example "Your house is burning" to show statements aim at practical effects, not mere intellectual assent. Relates disbelief as the basis for misinterpretation of statements and knowledge.

**AI Recommendation:** Major essay developing Monasterio's alternative to representationalist theories of language.

